\end_inset

Recall:
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a matrix,
 a nonzero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is said to be an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is a scalar multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{v}=\lambda\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 for some number 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 In this case,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is said to be the eigenvalue associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
In the following items,
 assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

,
 and that it is also an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 
\shape italic
You may not assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are diagonalizable.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

