Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 With what eigenvalue?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 With what eigenvalue?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $7A$
\end_inset

.
 With what eigenvalue?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

.
 With what eigenvalue?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution
We apply each matrix to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 and see what we get in each case:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

label=(
\backslash
alph*)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $A^{3}\vec{v}=AAA\vec{v}=AA(\lambda\vec{v})=\lambda AA\vec{v}=\lambda A(\lambda\vec{v})=\lambda^{2}A\vec{v}=\lambda^{3}\vec{v}$
\end_inset

,
 so the eigenvalue is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{v}=\lambda\vec{v}$
\end_inset

,
 multiplying both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\lambda A^{-1}\vec{v}$
\end_inset

,
 hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}\vec{v}=\frac{1}{\lambda}\vec{v}$
\end_inset

,
 so the eigenvalue is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(7A)\vec{v}=7\lambda\vec{v}$
\end_inset

,
 so the eigenvalue is 
\begin_inset Formula $7\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(A+B)\vec{v}=A\vec{v}+B\vec{v}=\lambda\vec{v}+\mu\vec{v}=(\lambda+\mu)\vec{v}$
\end_inset

,
 so the eigenvalue is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda+\mu$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
