Decide whether each of the following statements is true or false.
 If it is true,
 give an example.
 If it is false,
 prove that there is no such example.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

label=(
\backslash
alph*)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

An eigenvalue of a matrix can be associated to multiple eigenvectors,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An eigenvector of a matrix can be associated to multiple eigenvalues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Comment on the following attempted solution to part (b):
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is any matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\vec{0}$
\end_inset

,
 both of the following equations are true:
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{v}=1\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{v}=2\vec{v}$
\end_inset

.
 As a consequence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 and it's associated to both the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 yes,
 an eigenvector can be associated to multiple eigenvalues.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution
(a) This is true.
 For example,
 consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

,
 and the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 These are both eigenvectors associated to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

.
 In fact,
 any two vectors (e.g.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\vec{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\vec{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

) would have worked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
(b) This is false.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 be an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 and suppose that it is associated to two distinct eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{v}=\mu\vec{v}=\lambda\vec{v}$
\end_inset

,
 and so we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu-\lambda)\vec{v}=\vec{0}$
\end_inset

.
 However,
 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is not the zero vector (by definition of eigenvector),
 so there is some component 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 by the previous equality we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu-\lambda)v_{i}=0$
\end_inset

,
 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\neq0$
\end_inset

 we conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu-\lambda=0$
\end_inset

,
 or in other words,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 But we assumed that these two eigenvalues were distinct,
 and so we have a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
(c) The solution is correct up to the point where it claims that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 because the definition of eigenvector explicitly requires that the vector is not zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
7.1.15
\end_layout

\end_inset

Arguing geometrically,
 find an eigenbasis for the linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{2}\to\R^{2}$
\end_inset

 that consists of reflection about a line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 passing through the origin.
 Your eigenbasis may be represented through a sketch or a description.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
One eigenvector consists of any nonzero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 on the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 This has eigenvalue 1,
 because the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is unchanged by reflection about itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
For the second eigenvector,
 pick any nonzero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

 perpendicular to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 This will be reflected to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 so this eigenvector has eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
7.4.38,
 modified,
 
