\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Leonardo of Pisa (c.
 1170-1240),
 also known as Fibonacci,
 was the first outstanding European mathematician after the ancient Greeks.
 He traveled widely in the Islamic world and studied Arabic mathematical writing.
 His work is in the spirit of the Arabic mathematics of his day.
 Fibonacci brought the decimal-position system to Europe.
 In his book 
\shape italic
Liber abaci
\shape default
 (1202),
 Fibonacci discusses the following problem:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Quotation
How many pairs of rabbits can be bred from one pair in one year?
 A man has one pair of rabbits at a certain place entirely surrounded by a wall.
 We wish to know how many pairs can be bred from it in one year,
 if the nature of these rabbits is such that they breed every month one other pair and begin to breed in the second month after their birth.
 Let the first pair breed a pair in the first month,
 then there will be 2 pairs in a month.
 From these pairs one,
 namely,
 the first,
 breeds a pair in the second month,
 and thus there are 3 pairs in the second month.
 From these,
 in one month,
 two will become pregnant,
 so that in the third month 2 pairs of rabbits will be born.
 Thus,
 there are 5 pairs in this month.
 From these,
 in the same month,
 3 will be pregnant,
 so that in the fourth month there will be 8 pairs.
 From these pairs,
 5 will breed 5 other pairs,
 which,
 added to the 8 pairs,
 gives 13 pairs in the fifth month,
 from which 5 pairs (which were bred in that same month) will not conceive in that month,
 but the other 8 will be pregnant.
 Thus,
 there will be 21 pairs in the sixth month.
 When we add to these the 13 pairs that are bred in the seventh month,
 then there will be in that month 34 pairs [and so on,
 
\begin_inset Formula $55,89,144,233,377,\ldots$
\end_inset

 ].
 Finally,
 there will be 377,
 and this number of pairs has been born from the first-mentioned pair at the given place in one year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $j(t)$
\end_inset

 be the number of juvenile pairs and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

 the number of adult pairs after 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 months.
 Fibonacci starts his thought experiment in rabbit breeding with one adult pair,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $j(0)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(0)=1$
\end_inset

.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

,
 the adult pair will have bred a (juvenile) pair,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $a(1)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(1)=1$
\end_inset

.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $t=2$
\end_inset

,
 the initial adult pair will have bred another (juvenile) pair,
 and last month's juvenile pair will have grown up,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $a(2)=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(2)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Find formulas expressing 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t+1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(t+1)$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Find the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t+1)=A\vec{x}(t)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t)=(a(t),j(t))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Find closed formulas for 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Note:
 You will have to deal with irrational quantities here.
 You should use exact forms and not round.
 I recommend giving the two eigenvalues names,
 like 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 and referring to these names instead of the entire expression.
 This will make your work easier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Find the limit of the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)/j(t)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 approaches infinity.
 (Hint:
 It may be useful to plug the two eigenvalues you got into a calculator,
 to see which is bigger.) This number is known as 
\emph on
the golden ratio
\emph default
.
 Interpret your answer by completing the following sentence:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

For very large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 we will have approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\phantom{blah}}\%$
\end_inset

 more adult rabbits than juvenile rabbits
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 (Use a decimal approximation.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let us forget,
 for a moment,
 the original context of pairs of rabbits,
 so that we are allowed to set 
\begin_inset Formula $a(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(0)$
\end_inset

 to be negative numbers,
 fractional numbers,
 etc.
 However,
 the rule for 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t+1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(t+1)$
\end_inset

 remains the same.
 Can you find 
\begin_inset Formula $a(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(0)$
\end_inset

,
 not both equal to zero,
 such that,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 approaches infinity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

 approaches zero?
 Why or why not?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a(t+1)=a(t)+j(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(t+1)=a(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t)=(a(t),j(t))$
\end_inset

,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{x}(t+1)=A\vec{x}(t),\text{ where }A=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
First,
 we diagonalize 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 To find the eigenvalues,
 we solve 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A-\lambda I)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We know 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A-\lambda I)=(1-\lambda)\lambda-1=-\lambda^{2}+\lambda-1$
\end_inset

.
 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $-\lambda^{2}+\lambda-1=0$
\end_inset

 with the quadratic formula,
 we get two values:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{1}=\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}\text{ and }\lambda_{2}=\frac{1-\sqrt{5}}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Now,
 we find a vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker(A-\lambda_{1}I)$
\end_inset

.
 Such a vector is,
 for example,
 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,\lambda_{1}-1)$
\end_inset

,
 which is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,-\lambda_{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 we find a vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker(A-\lambda_{2}I)$
\end_inset

.
 Such a vector is,
 for example (like in the previous case) 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,-\lambda_{1})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A=SDS^{-1}$
\end_inset

,
 with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
-\lambda_{2} & -\lambda_{1}
\end{bmatrix},\text{ and }D=\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_{1} & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2}
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain closed formulas,
 we need to invert the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Using the Gauss-Jordan method,
 we could obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{-1}=\begin{bmatrix}1+\frac{\lambda_{2}}{\sqrt{5}} & \frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\\
-\frac{\lambda_{2}}{\sqrt{5}} & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}
\end{bmatrix}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_{1} & 1\\
-\lambda_{2} & -1
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\vec{x}(t) & =A^{t}(1,0)\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
-\lambda_{2} & -\lambda_{1}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_{1}^{t} & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2}^{t}
\end{bmatrix}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_{1} & 1\\
-\lambda_{2} & -1
\end{bmatrix}\right)\begin{bmatrix}1\\
0
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
-\lambda_{2} & -\lambda_{1}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_{1}^{t} & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{2}^{t}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_{1}\\
-\lambda_{2}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
-\lambda_{2} & -\lambda_{1}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_{1}^{t+1}\\
-\lambda_{2}^{t+1}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_{1}^{t+1}-\lambda_{2}^{t+1}\\
-\lambda_{2}\lambda_{1}^{t+1}+\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}^{t+1}
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So we have the closed formula:
 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\left(\lambda_{1}^{t+1}-\lambda_{2}^{t+1}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(t)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\left(-\lambda_{2}\lambda_{1}^{t+1}+\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}^{t+1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 (Using the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}=-1$
\end_inset

,
 we can actually simplify 
\begin_inset Formula $j(t)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\left(\lambda_{1}^{t}-\lambda_{2}^{t}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which makes sense given that 
\begin_inset Formula $j(t)=a(t-1)$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
As 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 approaches infinity,
 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t)$
\end_inset

 will get closer to the line spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,-\lambda_{2})$
\end_inset

,
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 is smaller than one in absolute value.
 Thus,
 we expect that 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)/j(t)\to1/(-\lambda_{2})=\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
As an alternate approach,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\left(\lambda_{1}^{t+1}-\lambda_{2}^{t+1}\right)}{\frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}\left(\lambda_{1}^{t}-\lambda_{2}^{t}\right)}=\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{\lambda_{1}^{t+1}-\lambda_{2}^{t+1}}{\lambda_{1}^{t}-\lambda_{2}^{t}},
\]

\end_inset

and in both the denominator and numerator the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 term dominates,
 and thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{\lambda_{1}^{t+1}-\lambda_{2}^{t+1}}{\lambda_{1}^{t}-\lambda_{2}^{t}}=\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{\lambda_{1}^{t+1}}{\lambda_{1}^{t}}=\lim_{t\to\infty}\lambda_{1}=\lambda_{1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We interpret this as follows.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $1.62$
\end_inset

,
 we conclude:
 For very large values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 we will have approximately 62% more adult rabbits than juvenile rabbits.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Geometrically,
 we want a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(0)$
\end_inset

 that only has a component of the eigenvector associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

,
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}^{t}\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 I would choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(0)=(1,-\lambda_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 In this case,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}(t)=(\lambda_{2}^{t},-\lambda_{2}^{t}\lambda_{1})$
\end_inset

 which converges to zero.
 In other words,
 I would set 
\begin_inset Formula $a(0)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j(0)=-\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
7.3.14
\end_layout

\end_inset

(Uses material from class on Tuesday W9) Diagonalize the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
-5 & 0 & 2\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
First,
 we find the eigenvalues by using the characteristic polynomial.
 The characteristic polynomial is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(\lambda)=\det\begin{bmatrix}1-\lambda & 0 & 0\\
-5 & -\lambda & 2\\
0 & 0 & 1-\lambda
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

which may be calculated by Laplace expansion on,
 say,
 the first row,
 to get 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\lambda)=(1-\lambda)\det\left[\begin{smallmatrix}-\lambda & 2\\
0 & 1-\lambda
\end{smallmatrix}\right]=(1-\lambda)(-\lambda)(1-\lambda)$
\end_inset

.
 We see that this polynomial has roots:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

,
 with multiplicity 1,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

,
 with multiplicity 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
To find the eigenvector associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

,
 we find a vector in the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 An easy example is 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{1}=(0,1,0)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

,
 since its algebraic multiplicity is 2,
 we expect to find a basis of the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $A-I$
\end_inset

 with two elements.
 We start by writing out 
\begin_inset Formula $A-I$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A-I=\begin{bmatrix}0 & 0 & 0\\
-5 & 1 & 2\\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

and it's not hard to see that its row-reduced form is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}1 & -\frac{1}{5} & -\frac{2}{5}\\
0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

whence a basis of the kernel is given by the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{2}=(1,5,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{3}=(2,0,5)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 we can diagonalize our matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $SDS^{-1}$
\end_inset

,
 with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\begin{bmatrix}0 & 1 & 2\\
1 & 5 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 5
\end{bmatrix}\text{ and }D=\begin{bmatrix}0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
The solution is complete.
\end_layout

